{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652088"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18509"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18509"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.05,0.05,0.71,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11238"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76318"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11238"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61827"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7463"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26317"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76318"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ankle joint is stabilised by several important ligamentous structures that prevent excessive movement and maintain joint integrity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the lateral ligament complex of the ankle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Four ligaments connecting tibia to calcaneus","Single broad ligament connecting fibula to calcaneus","Two ligaments connecting tibia to talus","Three separate ligaments connecting fibula to talus and calcaneus","Five ligaments connecting fibula to navicular"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethree separate ligaments connecting fibula to talus and calcaneus\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the lateral ligament complex of the ankle. These three ligaments are the anterior talofibular ligament, calcaneofibular ligament, and posterior talofibular ligament (image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFour ligaments connecting tibia to calcaneus\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as the lateral ligaments connect to the fibula, not the tibia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle broad ligament connecting fibula to calcaneus\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes only the calcaneofibular ligament, which is just one component of the lateral complex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwo ligaments connecting tibia to talus\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes components of the deltoid ligament on the medial side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive ligaments connecting fibula to navicular\u003C/strong\u003E - The lateral ligaments do not attach to the navicular bone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lateral ligament complex provides stability against inversion of the ankle. The anterior talofibular ligament is the most commonly injured component during inversion injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The lateral ligament complex of the ankle consists of three separate ligaments: anterior talofibular, calcaneofibular, and posterior talofibular.","The anterior talofibular ligament connects the lateral malleolus to the talus and resists anterior translation and inversion.","The lateral ligament complex provides stability against inversion and is commonly injured in ankle sprains."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022","\u201cLateral collateral ligament of ankle joint\u201d by Laboratoires Servier is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Lateral_collateral_ligament_of_ankle_joint.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61827"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18509"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21415"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21415"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jqEEdg8my2Ufjv4E47pNFmKwhjHnVK.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jqEEdg8my2Ufjv4E47pNFmKwhjHnVK.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":458}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61827"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T03:32:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T03:33:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11238"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76318"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":